{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"16f72ad7-896f-42f9-ae61-e666672f0544","content":"I don't have a specialized skill for **analyzing** crash dumps (only for collecting them). However, here's how you can analyze your `.dmp` file:\n\n### Recommended tool: `dotnet-dump analyze`\n\n```bash\n# Install if needed\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze <your-file>.dmp\n```\n\nOnce inside, useful commands:\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `pe` (PrintException) | Show last exception details |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary |\n| `setthread <id>` then `clrstack` | Inspect other threads |\n\n### Quick triage flow\n1. **`pe`** — check if there's an unhandled exception\n2. **`clrthreads`** — find the faulting thread\n3. **`setthread <id>`** + **`clrstack`** — get its call stack\n\n### Alternatives\n- **Visual Studio** (Windows) — open the `.dmp` directly, click \"Debug with Managed Only\"\n- **WinDbg** + SOS — `!analyze -v`, then `!pe`, `!clrstack`\n- **lldb** + SOS (Linux/macOS)\n\nWould you like me to walk you through running `dotnet-dump analyze` on your file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5c5e80e1-2955-4207-b7f9-cbd689361f86","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET application and wants to analyze it. Let me check if there's a relevant skill available for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills:\n- `dump-collect` - This is for **collecting** crash dumps, NOT analyzing them. The description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\"\n- `dotnet-trace-collect` - For capturing diagnostic artifacts, not analyzing dumps\n- `android-tombstone-symbolication` - For Android tombstone files\n- `apple-crash-symbolication` - For Apple .ips crash logs\n\n\nNone of these skills can help with analyzing .dmp files, so I'll need to guide the user through the manual process using standard debugging tools like WinDbg or dotnet-dump.","outputTokens":558,"requestId":"418B:21AE1A:61931B2:6ADE423:69F164BE"},"id":"af60b6ef-eac8-4b15-891f-d2009dbf4028","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:54:21.573Z","parentId":"e05a42bc-5722-4451-8583-7616f6fbde28"}
